In Java, control statements determine the flow of execution in a program. 
   They decide which code runs, how many times it runs, and under what conditions.

1.Decision-Making Statements (Conditional Statements)
  These execute code based on conditions.
  if Statement
  Executes a block if the condition is true.
Example:
int age = 18;

if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("You are an adult.");
}
  if-else Statement
  Executes one block if true, another if false.
 Example:
int number = 5;

if (number % 2 == 0) {
  System.out.println("Even");
} else {
    System.out.println("Odd");
}

if-else-if Ladder
Used when checking multiple conditions.
Example:
int marks = 75;

if (marks >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade A");
} else if (marks >= 70) {
    System.out.println("Grade B");
} else {
    System.out.println("Grade C");
}

2.Looping Statements (Iteration Statements)
  Used to repeat a block of code.

  for Loop
  Used when the number of iterations is known.
  Example:
  for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
  }
  while Loop
   Executes while the condition is true.
  Example:
  int i = 1;
  while (i <= 5) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
  }
  do-while Loop
  Executes at least once before checking the condition.
  Example:
  int i = 1;
  do {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
  } while (i <= 5);

3.Jump Statements (Branching Statements)
  Used to alter the normal flow of execution.

  break
  Terminates the loop or switch.
  Example:
   for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) {
        break;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
    }

   continue
   Skips the current iteration.
   Example:
    for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    if (i == 3) {
        continue;
    }
    System.out.println(i);
    }

    return
    Exits from a method.
    Example:
    public static int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
    }

